## 1. Advanced Joins

### 1.1 Self join
```sql
-- Find employees earning more than their manager
SELECT e.name AS employee, m.name AS manager, e.salary, m.salary AS manager_salary
FROM employees e
JOIN employees m ON e.manager_id = m.id
WHERE e.salary > m.salary;
```

### 1.2 Semi join (EXISTS) vs Anti join (NOT EXISTS)
```sql
-- Semi join: customers who HAVE placed an order (don't need order columns)
SELECT c.*
FROM customers c
WHERE EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM orders o WHERE o.customer_id = c.id);

-- Anti join: customers who have NEVER ordered
SELECT c.*
FROM customers c
WHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM orders o WHERE o.customer_id = c.id);
```
`NOT EXISTS` is generally safer than `NOT IN` because `NOT IN` breaks silently if the subquery returns a NULL.

### 1.3 LATERAL join (correlated join per row — top-N per group)
```sql
-- Top 3 most recent orders per customer
SELECT c.id, o.*
FROM customers c
CROSS JOIN LATERAL (
    SELECT o2.*
    FROM orders o2
    WHERE o2.customer_id = c.id
    ORDER BY o2.order_date DESC
    LIMIT 3
) o;
```
BigQuery equivalent concept: correlated subqueries or `ARRAY_AGG` with `ORDER BY ... LIMIT`.

### 1.4 Non-equi / range joins
```sql
-- Assign each transaction to a price tier based on a range table
SELECT t.id, t.amount, tier.tier_name
FROM transactions t
JOIN price_tiers tier
  ON t.amount BETWEEN tier.min_amount AND tier.max_amount;
```

