## 9. Data warehousing patterns (star schema, SCD, upserts)

### 9.1 Slowly Changing Dimension Type 2 (extremely common DE interview question)
```sql
-- Close out old version, insert new version, in one transaction
BEGIN;

UPDATE dim_customer
SET valid_to = CURRENT_DATE, is_current = FALSE
WHERE customer_id = 123 AND is_current = TRUE;

INSERT INTO dim_customer (customer_id, name, address, valid_from, valid_to, is_current)
VALUES (123, 'New Name', 'New Address', CURRENT_DATE, NULL, TRUE);

COMMIT;
```

### 9.2 Idempotent upsert / MERGE (core of most incremental dbt models)
```sql
MERGE INTO target_table AS t
USING staging_table AS s
ON t.id = s.id
WHEN MATCHED AND t.updated_at < s.updated_at THEN
    UPDATE SET name = s.name, updated_at = s.updated_at
WHEN NOT MATCHED THEN
    INSERT (id, name, updated_at)
    VALUES (s.id, s.name, s.updated_at);
```
PostgreSQL alternative (`ON CONFLICT`):
```sql
INSERT INTO target_table (id, name, updated_at)
VALUES (1, 'Alice', now())
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE
SET name = EXCLUDED.name, updated_at = EXCLUDED.updated_at
WHERE target_table.updated_at < EXCLUDED.updated_at;
```

### 9.3 Star schema fact query
```sql
SELECT
    d.year, d.month,
    p.category,
    SUM(f.quantity * f.unit_price) AS revenue
FROM fact_sales f
JOIN dim_date d ON f.date_key = d.date_key
JOIN dim_product p ON f.product_key = p.product_key
GROUP BY d.year, d.month, p.category;
```

