## 13. Data quality checks in SQL (the dbt-test mindset)
```sql
-- Uniqueness check
SELECT id, COUNT(*)
FROM dim_customer
GROUP BY id
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1;

-- Referential integrity check (orphan foreign keys)
SELECT o.id
FROM orders o
LEFT JOIN customers c ON o.customer_id = c.id
WHERE c.id IS NULL;

-- Freshness check
SELECT MAX(loaded_at) AS last_load, now() - MAX(loaded_at) AS staleness
FROM raw_events;

-- Null/completeness check
SELECT
    COUNT(*) AS total_rows,
    COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE email IS NULL) AS missing_email
FROM customers;
```
In practice on NL projects this logic usually lives as **dbt tests** (`unique`, `not_null`, `relationships`, `accepted_values`) rather than raw SQL — worth learning dbt alongside SQL itself.

